 <h2>
  <span class="mw-headline">
   The Disease
  </span>
 </h2>
 <p>
  <i>
   Salmonella enterica
  </i>
  serovar Typhimurium (
  <i>
   S
  </i>
  . Typhimurium) infection is normally associated with self-limiting gastroenteritis, and systemic disease is rare in most parts of the world. However, a highly invasive form of nontyphoidal
  <i>
   Salmonella
  </i>
  (NTS) disease, frequently associated with
  <i>
   S.
  </i>
  Typhimurium isolates, has emerged as a major public health problem in sub-Saharan Africa.
  <i>
   S
  </i>
  . Typhimurium strain D23580 was isolated from the blood of a Malawian 26 month old child with malaria and anemia admitted to Queen Elizabeth Central Hospital, Blantyre, Malawi, in January 2004.
 </p>
 <a name="The_Genome">
 </a>
 <h2>
  <span class="mw-headline">
   The Genome
  </span>
 </h2>
 <p>
  The
  <i>
   S
  </i>
  . Typhimurium strain D23580 genome is composed of a single circular chromosome of 4,879,400 bp, and a plasmid (pSLT-BT) of 117,047 bp, and was sequenced in collaboration with Dr. Samuel Kariuki of the Centre for Microbiology Research,
  <a href="http://www.kemri.org/" class="external text" title="http://www.kemri.org/" rel="nofollow">
   Kenya Medical Research Institute
  </a>
  , Nairobi, Kenya, and Dr. Robert Heyderman of the
  <a href="http://www.mlw.medcol.mw/" class="external text" title="http://www.mlw.medcol.mw/" rel="nofollow">
   Malawi-Liverpool-Wellcome Trust Clinical Research Programme
  </a>
  , University of Malawi College of Medicine, Blantyre, Malawi.
 </p>
